The separation efficiency of charge carriers of as-prepared pure BOR, UCN, CCN, and BCCN-30 composites was determined by PC and EIS experiments. As shown in Fig. 11
                        a, pure BOR and UCN have weak photocurrent intensity because of the low separation efficiency of the photogenerated carriers. However, the photocurrent of CCN composite is higher than that of pure BOR and CCN, and BCCN-30 exhibits the highest photocurrent intensity. This phenomenon can be ascribed to CDs serving as the charge transmission bridge material in the middle of BOR and UCN. The excited e− on the CB of BOR and the photogenerated h+ on the VB of UCN are transferred to CDs, leading to photogenerated e− concentrated on the CB of UCN and h+ accumulated on the VB of BOR (Fig. 12
                        ). To demonstrate the mobility and separation of photoexcited carriers, EIS of as-synthesized photocatalyst is detected, and the EIS Nyquist plots of the two photoelectrodes in the dark are displayed in Fig. 11b. The diameter of the semicircle of the EIS Nyquist plots is related to the transfer efficiency of photoinduced carriers, and the smaller radius represents higher separation efficiency. Compared with pure BOR, UCN, and CCN, a smaller arc radius is found for BCCN-30 composite, which is evidence of high photoactivity. The above results are well consistent with the detection data of the photocurrent experiment.
